Connect1-Stigma: 3. Classification tree

Classification trees

Method

A classification tree uses different predictors to sequentially sort cases into purer categories of outcomes, with the end goal of knowing which sequence and/or cutoff values of predictors leads to having an outcome of A or B. This is a different strategy compared to logistic regression, which uses a weighted combination of predictors to calculate a probability of the outcome being A or B. One advantage of classification trees over logistic regression is that the results are easier to interpret. There is a trade-off between the simplicity of the tree and its accuracy; selecting a stricter criterion (complexity parameter) so that fewer branches are allowed to grow makes the results easier to interpret, but tends to decrease the classification accuracy of the tree.

The participants in this analysis were n=753 who have a four-frequency PTA of > 25 dB HL in their better ear and no missing data in 28 predictor variables and 1 outcome variable. Because there are about four times as many No cases as Yes cases, I added case weights so that there was an equivalent number of each type of response, so that the model would not be biased towards No cases (Yes cases were weighted 1, and No cases were weighted 0.2467).

As before, the data were split into 7 similarly-sized folds, and a classification tree was built for 7 subsets of data, dropping out 1 fold each time. For each subset of data, I tried four different complexity parameters, which gave various numbers of splits in the tree, to see the effect of the tree complexity on model performance.

Results

A very complex tree with 23 splits led to 78% accuracy, the highest accuracy reached in the plot below, but pruning a tree to fewer splits didnt really affect accuracy. (The colours refer to different subsets of data.)

A complex tree does have better sensitivity and specificity than a simple tree, however. (The colours refer to ranges of splits in the trees.)

Using all the data and letting the tree grow to its maximum complexity (41 splits), the accuracy of the model is 78%, with 93% sensitivity and 75% specificity. The results are not easy to interpret, however, as there are many different pathways that could lead to a Yes or No decision.

Using all the data and letting the tree grow just to the number of splits where the models error rate is within one standard deviation of the lowest possible error rate (there is a procedure built into the function that looks at this) the tree has 3 splits, with 67% accuracy, 59% sensitivity, and 69% specificity. (This tree is basically the top two levels of the complex tree above; it was not allowed to grow past the first three splits.)

Conclusion

The best classification tree in terms of interpretability and accuracy has 3 splits that use HHIE, PTA and Age to predict who decided to purchase hearing aids. This models accuracy isnt much better than NRI or just a plain logistic regression model, but it provides more information than previous analyses by showing exactly how Age and HHIE lead to a Yes or No purchase outcome.
